Here&#39;s an example in Java

    public class Mammal {
        public final int getNumberOfLegs() {
            return 4;
        }
    }

    public class Human extends Mammal {
        @Override                        &lt;&lt;-- compilation error!
        public int getNumberOfLegs() {
            return 2;
        }
    }


Here I have declared `Mammal`&#39;s method `getNumberOfLegs()` to be `final`, which means that it is not permitted to override the method in a child class.

  - When I try to override it in a child class, I get a compilation error.
  - If I *need* to override it (as in this example where people have an unusual number of legs), then I have a big problem.

Now imagine what would happen if Java didn&#39;t allow me to override *any* methods in a child class.  I would not be able to implement any methods with a different behavior in a child class.  

 - In some simple cases I will be able to work around this.  (In this one, I could add a `numberOfLegs` field to all `Mammal` objects.) 

 - In other cases it would be more difficult to share common behavior in a class hierarchy.  (In my contrived example, you can imagine that I didn&#39;t anticipate that `getNumberOfLegs()` *might* need to be implemented differently in a child class.)  Now clearly you can change behavior by modifying the code the parent class rather than overriding it in a child class.  However:

     - this reduces your options as a programmer, and
     - it also leads to parent classes having too much knowledge about current and (possible) future child classes.

